main event: Multiple sightings of unusual lights at Keflavik Airport on 3/19/53 with no physical evidence or photographs. The lights were described as bright, round, and stationary.
interesting points: The radar plots observed on February 3, 1953, showed unidentified high-speed targets at altitudes of 25,000 to 30,000 feet, moving at speeds of 700 to 800 knots.
No identified aircraft from known sources could explain the radar plots, and the apparent lack of motion during two full minutes in one instance remained unexplained.
The report mentions large flocks of geese in the vicinity, indicating the consideration of natural explanations alongside the unidentified radar plots.
The document includes a handwritten note with the text 'UNCLE, 1952+ 17:45, ADUTANOUS OVER', providing potential additional context or codes related to the sightings.
The report was investigated by the Intelligence Officer of the USAF and was concluded as 'UNIDENTIFIED', indicating a lack of explanation for the observed phenomena.
